id like dexamethasone, the body's own ACTH production should decrease because of negative feedback.","dimension":1,"group":7,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.043216,0.065854,0.08234,0.093339,0.10256,0.10479,0.10449,0.10054,0.094565,0.083176,0.069832,0.0553],"unified_progress":[0.044104,0.074598,0.091181,0.098589,0.10431,0.10606,0.10507,0.094889,0.088099,0.079829,0.065747,0.047524]},{"section":11,"text":"But in this case, the ACTH level didn't go down, which suggests that the feedback mechanism isn't working properly.","dimension":1,"group":7,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.038755,0.061978,0.078243,0.089629,0.098334,0.10167,0.10295,0.10134,0.09809,0.089694,0.077356,0.061961],"unified_progress":[0.041803,0.072124,0.088137,0.096183,0.10222,0.1027,0.10313,0.096393,0.090724,0.084913,0.070426,0.051238]},{"section":12,"text":"So, what causes ACTH levels to remain high despite dexamethasone?","dimension":3,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.031272,0.056299,0.075763,0.08698,0.09895,0.10349,0.10341,0.10282,0.099125,0.094514,0.080478,0.066896],"unified_progress":[0.036848,0.069954,0.088012,0.098474,0.10288,0.10536,0.10464,0.096866,0.090112,0.085161,0.069979,0.051712]},{"section":13,"text":"One possibility is a pituitary tumor that's secreting ACTH, known as Cushing's disease.","dimension":15,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.03098,0.055337,0.072278,0.084584,0.095706,0.10188,0.10781,0.10815,0.10402,0.095042,0.080149,0.064068],"unified_progress":[0.037833,0.067526,0.085283,0.096401,0.10166,0.10564,0.10322,0.099287,0.093349,0.086575,0.070308,0.052912]},{"section":14,"text":"But wait, Cushing's disease usually causes elevated cortisol levels, which can lead to various symptoms like weight gain, especially in the trunk (truncal obesity), which the patient has.","dimension":15,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.036792,0.056923,0.072337,0.082336,0.092791,0.098247,0.10462,0.10626,0.10357,0.094833,0.083299,0.067989]